Input / Output in Java

ğŸ’¡ 1. What is Java I/O?

Java I/O (Input/Output) refers to the system of classes and interfaces that enable data reading (input) and writing (output) between a Java program and different data sources such as:

Files

Networks

Keyboard (System.in)

Console (System.out)

All these classes are available in the package:

import java.io.*;

ğŸ§  2. What is a Stream?

A Stream is a sequence of data that flows from one source to a destination.

Input Stream â†’ reads data from a source into the program.

Output Stream â†’ writes data from the program to a destination.

Think of it like water flowing through a pipe:

ğŸ’§ Input Stream â†’ data coming in
ğŸ’§ Output Stream â†’ data going out

ğŸ”¹ 3. InputStream and OutputStream Classes

These are abstract classes in java.io that form the foundation of byte-based I/O.

(a) InputStream

Used to read data in bytes.

Key methods:

int read()         // reads one byte
int read(byte[] b) // reads bytes into array
void close()       // closes the stream

(b) OutputStream

Used to write data in bytes.

Key methods:

void write(int b)        // writes one byte
void write(byte[] b)     // writes byte array
void flush()             // forces data to be written
void close()             // closes the stream

